{"action": "input", "code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    teal_rectangles = find_teal_rectangles(input_grid)\n    max_red_rectangle = find_max_red_rectangle(teal_rectangles)\n    return max_red_rectangle\ndef find_max_red_rectangle(teal_rectangles: List[Tuple[int, int, int, int]], input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a list of teal rectangles and an input grid, this function returns the rectangle that has the most red pixels.\n    If there are multiple rectangles with the same number of red pixels, the function returns the one with the smallest area.\n    \n    Args:\n    - teal_rectangles: a list of tuples where each tuple represents a teal rectangle in the grid. Each tuple contains\n                       four integers (x1, y1, x2, y2) representing the top-left and bottom-right coordinates of the rectangle.\n    - input_grid: a numpy ndarray representing the input grid. The grid is a 2D array of integers where each integer\n                  represents the color of the corresponding pixel in the grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    - A tuple containing four integers (x1, y1, x2, y2) representing the top-left and bottom-right coordinates of the\n      rectangle that has the most red pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    max_red_pixels = 0\n    max_red_rectangle = None\n    for rectangle in teal_rectangles:\n        x1, y1, x2, y2 = rectangle\n        red_pixels = 0\n        for i in range(x1, x2 + 1):\n            for j in range(y1, y2 + 1):\n                if input_grid[i][j] == red:\n                    red_pixels += 1\n        if red_pixels > max_red_pixels:\n            max_red_pixels = red_pixels\n            max_red_rectangle = rectangle\n        elif red_pixels == max_red_pixels:\n            if (x2 - x1 + 1) * (y2 - y1 + 1) < (max_red_rectangle[2] - max_red_rectangle[0] + 1) * (max_red_rectangle[3] - max_red_rectangle[1] + 1):\n                max_red_rectangle = rectangle\n    return max_red_rectangle\ndef find_teal_rectangles(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> List[Tuple[int, int, int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid, this function returns a list of tuples where each tuple represents a teal rectangle in the grid.\n    A teal rectangle is defined as a rectangle that contains only teal pixels (color code 8) and has a non-zero area.\n    The function uses a brute-force approach to find all possible rectangles in the grid and then filters out the ones\n    that are not teal rectangles.\n    \n    Args:\n    - input_grid: a numpy ndarray representing the input grid. The grid is a 2D array of integers where each integer\n                  represents the color of the corresponding pixel in the grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    - A list of tuples where each tuple represents a teal rectangle in the grid. Each tuple contains four integers\n      (x1, y1, x2, y2) representing the top-left and bottom-right coordinates of the rectangle.\n    \"\"\"\n    teal_rectangles = []\n    rows, cols = input_grid.shape\n    for i in range(rows):\n        for j in range(cols):\n            if input_grid[i][j] == teal:\n                for k in range(i, rows):\n                    for l in range(j, cols):\n                        if input_grid[k][l] != teal:\n                            break\n                        if (k - i + 1) * (l - j + 1) > 0:\n                            teal_rectangles.append((i, j, k, l))\n    return teal_rectangles", "user_code": "def main(input_grid:np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    teal_rectangles = `find the teal teal_rectangles from the input_grid which may have red and blue pixels`(input_grid)\n    max_red_rectangle = `find the rectangle which have the most red pixles in teal_rectangles`(teal_rectangles)\n    return max_red_rectangle\n    ", "gpt_code": "def find_max_red_rectangle(teal_rectangles: List[Tuple[int, int, int, int]], input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a list of teal rectangles and an input grid, this function r